{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7e8b4e29-99fb-4c64-bcc7-737dbd695acd","content":"The project doesn't exist yet at that path, but here's how to configure `mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport (the standard for VS Code agent mode):\n\nCreate `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace root:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\n        \"run\",\n        \"--project\",\n        \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"\n      ]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`command` / `args`** — runs `dotnet run --project <path>`. You can also use a published binary path instead.\n- Your MCP server must read JSON-RPC from **stdin** and write responses to **stdout** (don't write logs to stdout — use stderr).\n- If you need environment variables, add an `\"env\": { \"KEY\": \"value\" }` field.\n\nIf you've already published the server, you can point directly at the DLL:\n\n```json\n\"command\": \"dotnet\",\n\"args\": [\"src/MyMcpServer/bin/Release/net8.0/MyMcpServer.dll\"]\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3a943d7a-60f6-4a83-9a25-4dc977dd9247","outputTokens":334,"requestId":"CC2B:2E9247:7CB6795:8B05A84:69EAC14F"},"id":"5be6a35a-e914-4716-a83a-d9e851545035","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:03:19.231Z","parentId":"df9c3743-1a00-41f6-ab3f-fcdb160f0d2d"}
